Hi Aengus,



Thank you for your email. Yes, I have spoken to Chris at length about this =
situation and am happy to give you my account of last year=92s events.



I wrote quite a thorough statement for Chris=92s formal complaint document =
(I believe mine is the first one, Appendix 1), though at the time I was hop=
ing to keep my name anonymous; I thought giving a statement for Chris might=
 affect my potential involvement in one of the university=92s orchestras, a=
nd for the foreseeable should I want a performance career. I am also on the=
 Music Society Committee, and so feel obligated as such to keep any relatio=
nship with Mr Rosina cordial. However, if this is the only way in which the=
 system will allow me to give my account then so be it. I can only hope tha=
t your investigation will mitigate those risks.



The statement I have already written is in Chris=92s big complaint document=
, as I say =97 it was more an attempt to summarise the effects I had seen i=
n Chris over the year than an exact account of the events (I was not in the=
 orchestra last year, after all, and so witnessed a limited amount of Mr Ro=
sina=92s behaviour), but I am more than happy to precisely describe what I =
witnessed on the days in question. I will try to be as thorough as I can, s=
o I apologise for any overlap with my previous statement.



The events of 6th June were the clearest incidence in which I saw Mr Rosina=
=92s harassment. I was hoping to catch Chris before he had to dash off afte=
r orchestra rehearsal, just so I could greet him as it was his birthday. He=
=92d confided in me that he had been worried before the rehearsal about nee=
ding to leave it promptly as he had a CBSO Chorus rehearsal afterwards, and=
 since they awarded him a bursary to take part, it was important that he ge=
t there in time (I think orchestra finished at 6:30pm and his next rehearsa=
l started at 6:45pm at the CBSO Centre, so there just wasn=92t enough time =
for Chris to arrive punctually even if he did leave immediately). When it r=
eached 6:45pm and Chris still hadn=92t come out of the Elgar (several other=
 orchestra members had left, but not Chris), I was getting concerned, so I =
went into the hall to see if he was alright. I opened the door to the hall =
and Chris and Mr Rosina were right there in a very heated exchange. I don=
=92t remember many details of the conversation as I was a bit taken aback a=
nd didn=92t wish to interrupt, but the manner of each of them was quite cle=
ar: Mr Rosina seemed very accusatory and agitated, whereas Chris more calm =
but somewhat exasperated. The only exact comment I can recall is something =
to the effect of Mr Rosina asking Chris if he was accusing him of favouriti=
sm and Chris dismissing this, seeming in a hurry to leave. I thought it bes=
t that I leave the hall again, not really knowing the context and not wanti=
ng any part in the confrontation.

                While I waited outside again, there was a further 5 minutes=
 before Chris emerged, in which time I spoke to a few members of the orches=
tra who had seen the events of the rehearsal (and the ongoing interaction a=
s they departed) and expressed sympathy for Chris, despite Chris, as a post=
grad, not being particularly socially integrated with them. When Chris fina=
lly walked out, he was visibly very upset and frustrated; it took several o=
f us to speak to him and reassure him before he was in any state to cycle (=
these were mostly Chris=92s friends and I, Amira Campbell and Mark Mingard =
were also there and were the only ones willing to give their names when Chr=
is began writing his complaint =97 there were at least a further three memb=
ers of orchestra present but I don=92t think I can give their names, as the=
y didn=92t want to be involved with Chris=92s complaint in case it jeopardi=
sed their position in orchestra, or, indeed, their professional careers). W=
e were very conscious of Chris=92s bike accident a few months prior and wer=
e determined that he didn=92t leave until he was in a better frame of mind,=
 which took somewhere between 10 and 40 minutes (I wasn=92t checking the cl=
ock naturally, but I recall because I had a rehearsal at 8pm and Chris had =
only definitely departed half an hour or so before that).

The whole fiasco left Chris very bothered and upset =97 we discussed it lat=
er that evening after both of our rehearsals had ended, and Chris decided h=
e would recount the events to Rachael Gibson the following day. I was prese=
nt for this meeting, as moral support. I believe the result of this meeting=
 was a little vague: Chris was advised to avoid Mr Rosina as much as was po=
ssible (despite the biweekly, then practically daily, rehearsals the week o=
f the concert), and it was implied that Mr Rosina would be spoken to about =
the incident. I imagine a more precise minutes of the meeting was taken, as=
 Rachael did take notes to put on the University Music system.



I have less to recount, really, about June 24th; I did not witness any of M=
r Rosina=92s behaviour, I can only testify to the state it left Chris in af=
terwards. I was holding a workspace for Chris in the Bramall, so that when =
Chris left the rehearsal (to my memory, he had had to leave early to teach,=
 but had sorted all of this through Gavin) he could immediately attend to h=
is teaching commitments, which he delivered over Zoom. Due to this, when Ch=
ris had again not appeared in good time, I couldn=92t really leave the work=
 area, as it would only delay Chris further when he did arrive. Finally Chr=
is appeared, a few minutes after I expected him, and I can honestly say I=
=92ve never seen him so anxious, humiliated and distressed =97 he had a pan=
ic attack at this point. All I could do was comfort him, help him to breath=
e, and hope to get him into his lesson in enough of a composed state to get=
 through it, as there wasn=92t time to discuss it yet and I knew some of Ch=
ris=92s concern was due to his role as a tutor and not wanting to let down =
his pupils. I sat opposite Chris as he taught his lesson, then we discussed=
 the events of the rehearsal (I won=92t go into the events themselves, as I=
 did not bear witness to them and I imagine Chris has already described the=
m to you): he expressed his mental exhaustion, frustration and desperately =
not wanting to perform in the concert that evening as a result of this but =
feeling obliged to, and we, again, decided that he should speak to Rachael =
about what had happened, who then persuaded him that he should perform but,=
 again, avoid Mr Rosina at all costs. I couldn=92t attend the concert, as I=
 had been ill with COVID recently, but I heard that there were no further c=
onfrontations.

                This was the end of the direct incidents with Mr Rosina, to=
 my knowledge. I know Chris followed up with University Music, but they wer=
e limited in what they could do. All of this led to Chris deciding ultimate=
ly not to re-audition for his role as principal flute in orchestra again. I=
 may be biased, as we are close, but with two fellowships in flute performa=
nce and a long experience of playing in high-standard orchestras, it just s=
eems such a shame for the university orchestra to have lost out on such a p=
roficient player. Chris is probably too modest to have brought up to you ju=
st how skilled a player he is, but in my honest view, he is by far the most=
 qualified candidate for the role, which he had carried out for almost two =
years before this whole debacle. His performance standard aside, as a stude=
nt at the university, he should feel able to audition and take part in thes=
e ensembles, but the thought of last year=92s incidents continuing was enou=
gh for Chris to back out of the ensemble. In the end, I also ended up withd=
rawing my application for orchestra in September, as I was worried that pur=
ely by association I might be rejected/treated unfairly by Mr Rosina (this =
is a common feeling in the Music Society =97 again, I can=92t mention names=
 of people that don=92t want to be involved in this, but the orchestra has =
faced a problem where the most talented players are hesitant to audition du=
e to their knowledge that they are not liked by Mr Rosina). Chris and I are=
 also keen chamber musicians, playing in a saxophone quartet and as a duo, =
but due to these past incidents we haven=92t felt confident that should we =
take part in things like chamber platforms that only Mr Rosina presides ove=
r, we would get any valuable feedback.



I hope this is enough detail on the incidents in question, as well as the s=
ituation, as I understand it, since =97 if you have any other questions, I =
would be happy to answer them.



All the best,

Sam



